{"tid":2510133,"cid":18,"subCid":0,"title":"Why is Einstein > von Neumann in intelligence?","createTime":"2021-04-30T02:42:02.000Z","updateTime":"2021-04-30T06:53:37.000Z","uid":353278,"like":3,"dislike":2,"uniUserReply":11,"replies":[{"pid":"c4537cc0bd6d299517469c4ea08004703ad21490","tid":2510133,"uid":353278,"like":0,"dislike":0,"score":0,"citedBy":0,"replyTime":"2021-04-30T02:42:02.000Z","msg":"I'll end the argument right now. Here's a quote from Eugene Wigner, a Nobel-prize winning physicist who was friends with both Einstein and Von Neumann:<br />\n<br />\n&quot;I have known a great many intelligent people in my life. I knew Planck, von Laue and Heisenberg. Paul Dirac was my brother in law; Leo Szilard and Edward Teller have been among my closest friends; and Albert Einstein was a good friend, too. But none of them had a mind as quick and acute as Jancsi [John] von Neumann. I have often remarked this in the presence of those men and no one ever disputed.<br />\n<br />\nBut Einstein's understanding was deeper even than von Neumann's. His mind was both more penetrating and more original than von Neumann's. And that is a very remarkable statement. Einstein took an extraordinary pleasure in invention. Two of his greatest inventions are the Special and General Theories of Relativity; and for all of Jancsi's brilliance, he never produced anything as original.&quot;<br />\n<br />\n&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;<br />\n<br />\nIn terms of precocious, &ldquo;gee whiz he can calculate Pi to the 23,000th decimal place in his head!&rdquo; Johnny was unmatched. Nobody - for the exception of Ramanujan, whose talents in mathematics were unparalleled - could match Johnny&rsquo;s eidetic gifts. But that raises an interesting question about what we mean by &ldquo;intelligence.&rdquo;<br />\n<br />\nBoth men were incredibly prolific. Von Neumann was an incredible polymath (everything from game theory in economics to computational engineering, pure &amp; applied mathematics, etc.) but he didn&rsquo;t revolutionize an entire field like Einstein did. What Einstein accomplished hadn&rsquo;t been done in 250 years, and that was just one of his many gifts to humanity. Neumann&rsquo;s mind was quicker than anybody of his era, but Einstein&rsquo;s mind was both more penetrating and more original than Johnny&rsquo;s- and that isn&rsquo;t an indictment of Johnny, but a reminder of how incredible Einstein&rsquo;s accomplishments were."},{"pid":"782c4ec33928b0d13ba8bfe2b4691ca2614441ca","tid":2510133,"uid":118346,"like":1,"dislike":0,"score":1,"citedBy":0,"replyTime":"2021-04-30T02:48:42.000Z","msg":"全盛時期 da vinci 夠唔夠打？"},{"pid":"44d27deececc9478ee7a15731e5aecc9f0b1e7b9","tid":2510133,"uid":367224,"like":4,"dislike":0,"score":4,"citedBy":0,"replyTime":"2021-04-30T02:51:05.000Z","msg":"諗起之前個天才po<br />\n成日混淆天才同貢獻/成就高低"},{"pid":"10be0fddef5e5c8262542748e83b2afdbb53423c","tid":2510133,"uid":367224,"like":3,"dislike":0,"score":3,"citedBy":3,"replyTime":"2021-04-30T02:52:42.000Z","msg":"其實同傳統嘅小聰明vs大智慧有異曲同工之妙"},{"pid":"3501f4ea10a0c56aa3a8b1e289a03b8181be05de","tid":2510133,"uid":105798,"like":2,"dislike":0,"score":2,"citedBy":0,"replyTime":"2021-04-30T02:52:45.000Z","msg":"because Einstein is a jew"},{"pid":"76368de79adce9ce190faf619fb8008fc4e92390","tid":2510133,"uid":358542,"like":0,"dislike":0,"score":0,"citedBy":0,"replyTime":"2021-04-30T02:57:20.000Z","msg":"因為評價嗰位係物理佬"},{"pid":"f5657d3ced09c807671705f92e7d80088477e09e","tid":2510133,"uid":353278,"like":0,"dislike":0,"score":0,"quote":{"pid":"10be0fddef5e5c8262542748e83b2afdbb53423c","tid":2510133,"uid":367224,"like":3,"dislike":0,"score":3,"citedBy":3,"replyTime":"2021-04-30T02:52:42.000Z","msg":"其實同傳統嘅小聰明vs大智慧有異曲同工之妙"},"citedBy":0,"replyTime":"2021-04-30T03:20:14.000Z","msg":"